  :root {
    --section-y: 64px;
    --section-x: 20px;
    --nav-height: 56px;
  }
}

In tailwind.config.ts, extend the theme to reference these variables so you can write bg-[var(--bg-page)] as Tailwind classes.

---

## Typography

Use Inter for everything — both headings and body text. Load it via next/font/google in app/[locale]/layout.tsx.

Type scale:
- Display (hero heading): clamp(2.25rem, 6vw, 4.5rem), weight 700, line-height 1.2
- H2 (section headings): 2.5rem desktop / 2rem mobile, weight 600, line-height 1.2
- H3 (card headings): 1.5rem, weight 600, line-height 1.4
- Body large: 1.125rem, weight 400, line-height 1.6
- Body: 1rem, weight 400, line-height 1.6
- Overline: 0.75rem, weight 600, uppercase, letter-spacing 0.1em
- Label: 0.875rem, weight 600, line-height 1.4

---

## Translations

Use next-intl. The default locale is mk (Macedonian). English (en) is the second locale.

Set up middleware.ts to detect locale from the URL path. The app folder structure is app/[locale]/.

All user-facing text must come from useTranslations(). Never hardcode Macedonian or English strings in JSX.

Message files live in messages/mk.json and messages/en.json. Structure keys as section.element — for example hero.heading, services.truck.title, contact.submit.

The language toggle lives in the Navbar. It switches between /mk/... and /en/... using next-intl's router. Display it as a simple pill with the two locale codes: MK | EN.

---

## Theme toggle (dark/light mode)

Theme is controlled by a data-theme attribute on the <html> element. Never use prefers-color-scheme media queries to drive the theme — it must always be an explicit user toggle.

Store the user's preference in localStorage under the key "ms-theme". On initial load, read localStorage and apply the attribute before first paint to avoid a flash of the wrong theme.

The toggle button lives in the Navbar next to the language switcher.

---

## Navbar

Fixed at the top. Height is var(--nav-height). Background is var(--nav-bg) with backdrop-filter: blur(12px).

Add a bottom border (1px solid var(--nav-border)) only when the user has scrolled more than 20px — use a scroll event listener with useEffect for this.

Layout: logo on the left, nav links in the center, language toggle + theme toggle + primary CTA button on the right.

On mobile, hide the nav links and show a hamburger icon that opens a full-screen overlay menu.

---

## Buttons

Always use the shadcn Button component. Override its default variant styles in components/ui/button.tsx to use the CSS variables defined above.

Primary: background var(--btn-primary-bg), hover var(--btn-primary-bg-hover), text var(--btn-primary-text), box-shadow var(--btn-primary-shadow), border-radius var(--radius-button).

Secondary: background var(--btn-secondary-bg), hover var(--btn-secondary-bg-hover), text var(--btn-secondary-text), border 1px solid var(--btn-secondary-border), border-radius var(--radius-button).

---

## Cards

Use the shadcn Card component as the base. Apply these styles:
- Background: var(--card-bg)
- Border: 1px solid var(--card-border)
- Box-shadow: var(--card-shadow)
- Border-radius: var(--radius-card)
- On hover: background var(--card-bg-hover), border-color var(--card-border-hover), box-shadow var(--card-shadow-hover), transform translateY(-4px)
- Transition: background 280ms cubic-bezier(0.4,0,0.2,1), border-color 280ms, box-shadow 280ms, transform 280ms

---

## Section layout

Every section uses a consistent content wrapper: max-w-[1280px] mx-auto px-[var(--section-x)] py-[var(--section-y)].

Section backgrounds alternate. Light sections use var(--bg-page). The ServiceItems section and the Map section use a dark background that is always #020c1b regardless of the current theme — these two sections never change their background colour.

Page section order:
1. Navbar (fixed)
2. Hero — full viewport, scroll-driven canvas animation
3. About — light bg, company description, 3 stat blocks
4. Services — light bg, 3 transport cards (Truck, Maritime, Rail) with expand/collapse
5. ServiceItems — always dark (#020c1b), 2×3 grid of service icon cards
6. Sectors — light bg, alternating image + text layout (Logistics, Commercial, Finance)
7. Map — always dark (#020c1b), full-width D3 interactive map
8. Contact — light bg, 2-column (form left, contact info right)
9. Footer — dark bg

---

## Hero section (scroll-driven canvas animation)

The hero shows a video exported as a JPEG sequence, played frame-by-frame as the user scrolls. Frames are in public/hero-frames/ named frame-0001.jpg through frame-XXXX.jpg.

Implementation rules:
- A canvas element is position absolute, fills the full viewport, z-index 0
- An outer div is position relative with height 250vh — this is the scroll distance
- A sticky inner div (top 0, height 100vh) holds the canvas and all text content
- TOTAL_FRAMES constant must match the actual frame count — leave it as a clearly named constant so it is easy to update
- On scroll: progress = scrollY / (containerHeight - viewportHeight), frameIndex = Math.floor(progress * (TOTAL_FRAMES - 1))
- Use requestAnimationFrame to draw frames — only redraw when frameIndex changes
- Preload frame 1 immediately on mount, load the rest in the background
- Use useRef for the canvas element, frames array, and current frame index — never put these in React state
- A gradient overlay sits above the canvas for text legibility: linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(2,12,27,0.50) 0%, rgba(2,12,27,0.10) 40%, rgba(2,12,27,0.75) 100%)
- The heading, subheading, and CTA use Framer Motion useScroll + useTransform to fade and translate in as the user starts scrolling
- A bouncing ChevronDown icon at the bottom fades out once scrolling begins

---

## Map section

The map is a D3 + TopoJSON visualization. Integrate it as a client component in components/sections/Map.tsx using useEffect and useRef to mount D3 against a div ref.

Load world topology from: https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/world-atlas@2/countries-50m.json

The map draws animated arc routes from North Macedonia (lon 21.745, lat 41.608) to partner countries across Europe, with traveling particle dots along each route.

Replace any hardcoded colour values in the D3 code with CSS variable references using getComputedStyle to read them at runtime.

Guard the useEffect: if the svg ref already has children, return early to prevent re-initialisation on re-renders.

Section background is always #020c1b. Map container minimum height: 600px desktop, 400px mobile.

---

## Contact form

Use shadcn Form + react-hook-form + zod. Fields: Name, Title, Company Name, Email, Message. All required. Email must pass format validation. Put the zod schema in lib/validations/contact.ts. Handle submission with a Next.js server action. Show inline success/error feedback without page reload.

---

## General rules

Never hardcode colours, spacing, radii, or shadows — always CSS variables.
Never hardcode text strings in JSX — always useTranslations().
Never use !important anywhere.
Never use inline styles except when dynamically assigning a CSS variable value in JS.
Never animate width or height — always animate transform and opacity for performance.
Never initialise D3 more than once per component mount.
Never modify files in components/ui/ manually.
All images use next/image with explicit width, height, and alt attributes. The hero canvas is exempt.
Use named exports for all section components.
Only add 'use client' when the component genuinely needs browser APIs, event listeners, or hooks.
When in doubt about any design decision, refer back to tokens-ms.json before making assumptions.
